  }, "A Quick Introduction"), mdx("p", null, "Some will say rhetoric is old-school trickery. That it no longer works. That we\u2019re all much wiser now and can tell when we\u2019re being duped by crafty language. I disagree. Sneaky rhetoric is still prevalent in everyday conversations, in newspapers and websites of record, in posts shared by influential people, and in speeches by eloquent intellectuals. And it continues to impact how we perceive the world around us. I want to walk you through a sort of dictionary of this kind of rhetoric."), mdx("p", null, "Part of the reason why these sleights of hand get past us is because of our tendency, when listening to someone speak for instance, to be focused on whether or not we like that person, and not on whether or not that person is making any sense. Another reason is due to how we instinctively process information. Consider two well-known effects."), mdx("p", null, mdx("strong", {
